atus><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G006806/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Guyanese Indians watch Indian films as if their very existence depends upon it, and in significant ways it does.&amp;nbsp; This research looks at cinema as one of the major sources of cultural identity and renewal among the east Indians of Guyana.&amp;nbsp; The products of the Indian film industry cater to diverse international audiences; but there are few ethnographic studies that examine how these films frame the expectations and cultural life of their audiences or ? as in the Guyanese case ? become the primary source of cultural confirmation.&amp;nbsp; Between 1838 and 1917 two hundred thousand indentured laborers were transported from India to Guyana, where they became a significant majority in this Caribbean state.&amp;nbsp; Although Indian films provide a moralistic caricature of Indian realities, they authenticate a notion of ?Indianness? for Guyanese long severed from direct contact with the sub-continent.&amp;nbsp; In the context of persistent ethnic hostility between Afro? and Indo-Guyanese, Indian films denote a cultural ?intactness? that links east Indians to what Anderson has identified as an ?imagined community?.&amp;nbsp; This research looks at the ways in which cinema enables this enclave group to maintain its Indian identity.
